&lt;p>This wall may be part of the crushing house where waste was brought from the finger dumps to be crushed and taken past the kiln by tramway up to sidings for use as ballast on the railways, but this is not certain as little is recorded about it.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="turbine-house">Turbine House
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/36.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/36_hu_b41dbbe78285a462.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/36_hu_f83383b59cc91b3d.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="A small stone and brick building on the east bank of the river, at SX 56476 92166, is the Turbine House that provided electricity for the quarry"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Water was piped from the Red-a-ven brook to a turbine housed in this building, generating power for the quarry. Spent water was then released into a short brick-lined channel on the West side of the building to return to the brook.&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&lt;a class="link" href="http://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=MDV120311&amp;amp;resourceID=104" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Devon &amp;amp; Dartmoor HER - MDV120311 - Turbine building at Meldon Quarries&lt;/a>&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/37.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/37_hu_d9bebf4756daf8db.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/37_hu_9ce05d62af0f1c75.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="Base where the turbine once sat. Note the water exit channel to the right"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;em>My guess from this base and similar designs is that this was a horizontal turbine with a &lt;a class="link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pelton_wheel" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>pelton wheel&lt;/a> with one or more jets coming in from the side to power them. A central shaft would then have transferred power into a generator mounted directly above it &lt;cite>&amp;ndash;Simon&lt;/cite>&lt;/em>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/38.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/38_hu_6a4b2c8cbf3af151.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/38_hu_993838671e25bbb.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="The steel beam would have been used to position the turbine, and also to lift its cover or generator for servicing"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/39.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/39_hu_46b1d3e13adbce65.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/39_hu_c606100d1ad1d19f.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="The brick lined channel where waste water was released, having spent its energy"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Somewhere near to the turbine house there were once corrugated iron buildings that housed crushers. These worked previous spoil heaps, crushing limestone which was then loaded onto wagons on an incline that led to the railway sidings on the eastern edge of Meldon Viaduct.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="explosives-magazine">Explosives Magazine
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/40.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/40_hu_1f17aab6ebc5e6a9.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/40_hu_d2dfdc15aec35a1a.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="The explosives magazine, SX 56550 92162"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This stone ruin was once where explosives for the quarry were kept. Before each shift, the explosives handler would take only enough from here for that shift&amp;rsquo;s operation.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Such handlers were often selected from the most careful and thorough of the workers, and would avoid carrying any iron tools, or even removed iron hobnails from their boots to reduce the chance of sparks.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/41.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/41_hu_d39d3b0753a71617.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/41_hu_caca8da12c8d92c.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="Looking over the store, with the rockface at Meldon Pool in the background"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Although the walls are strong, explosives stores often had very weak roofs - typically made of stick and oilcloth. If there was an accident, then the force would be sent upwards instead of outwards and repairs to the building would therefore be relatively quick.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/42.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/42_hu_99488beb290626bc.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/42_hu_84aed500500d295.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="A ground anchor nearby"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This ground anchor looks very similar to those used through the 20th century to secure straining wires for telegraph and electricity poles. It was probably employed for a similar purpose here.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="mineshaft">Mineshaft
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/43.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/43_hu_2a6caf69b51ec37e.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/43_hu_7fb8e447b78d51fb.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="This ringed-pit at SX 56518 92088 is probably a capped mineshaft"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>There are mine shafts on the east bank of the river with two adits nearby, typical of tin mining. They exist as sub-circular hollows with rims of upcast soil on their downslope margins. They vary in diameter, most examples being in the area of 3 metres with one exceptional example of 6 metres.&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&lt;a class="link" href="https://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=MDV120322&amp;amp;resourceID=104" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Devon &amp;amp; Dartmoor HER - MDV120322 - Mine shafts east of Meldon Pool&lt;/a>&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/44.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/44_hu_2d53a9ba9ebacb19.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/44_hu_d684862291ab1873.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="Trees growing in a pit. SX 56661 92136"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This pit is part of a old tin-working gert running down towards the river. The gert ends at SX 56589 92163 where a spoil heap starts and ends closer to the river at SX 56562 92171, quite high above the surrounding ground.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="the-bottle-factory">The Bottle Factory
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/45.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/45_hu_9bb915c8f005ce8b.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/45_hu_37e7929f8cd7cbcf.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="Concrete buildings at SX 5668 9204"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>These modern buildings are associated with more recent quarrying after 1921. The site remained open for a further fifty years until around 1970 and provided stone for road metalling.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Before these buildings, there was a failed glass bottle operation on this site.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>From the late 19th century, investigations were being made concerning the production of granulite (a granular metamorphic rock) at Meldon. There seemed to be potential to establish both glass and china works at the site.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>There was little activity until 1920 when a syndicate from London decided to build a glass factory. Two furnaces were installed out of a planned 12, and about 500 men were required. However, by February 1921, the men had been laid off and new owners were being sought.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>No obvious features remain of a glass industry, but large amounts of broken glass fragments can be seen, mostly representing small medicine and cosmetic bottles. &lt;cite>&amp;ndash; (Western Morning News 29/03/1920&lt;/cite>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/46.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/46_hu_cd67cac915096ed.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/46_hu_7a7c2bdb677056f1.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="The Red-a-Ven Brook and possible take-off for the turbine"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
data-flex-basis="426px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="south-quarry">South Quarry
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/47.jpg"
width="1600"
height="900"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/47_hu_89fc884495d15437.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/meldon-and-the-west-okemont-valley/47_hu_f5f66e015982676.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="The track towards Meldon Dam with the Southern aplite quarry on the left, and the ruined pier of a bridge to the right"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="177"
